There is no such assumption in NUnit. In fact, I've made many posts warning users of this and we even have some documentation about the unreliablility of order assumptions WRT data attributes.

However, it's entirely possible that some particular test is making that assumption. One moment...

...I'm back! You're right about the Author tests. The recently added tests for multiple authors use `Is.EqualTo` to compare arrays but should use `Is.EquivalentTo`

@JustinRChou you added these tests last week, would you like to take on this issue to fix them?

@oznetmaster If you see others, please continue to report them. Too bad you didn't review @JustinRChou's PR last week!

        [Test]
        public void ManyProperties()
        {
            Test test5 = (Test)fixture.Tests[4];
            Assert.AreEqual(6, test5.Properties.Keys.Count);
            Assert.AreEqual("A", test5.Properties.Get("A"));
            Assert.AreEqual("B", test5.Properties.Get("B"));
            Assert.AreEqual("C", test5.Properties.Get("C"));
            Assert.AreEqual("D", test5.Properties.Get("D"));
            Assert.AreEqual("E", test5.Properties.Get("E"));
            Assert.AreEqual("F", test5.Properties.Get("F"));
        }

I am looking at some of the other attributes with `AllowMultiple == true`, so for that test, should it also test the order or be rewritten to use `Is.EquivalentTo`?

And the `DatapointAttribute` and `DatapointsAttribute`, should they be updated with `[Obsolete]` or just update the tests to use `DatapointSourceAttribute`?
